<!--
    emblem_welcome.xml  — v3

    ─── WHAT CHANGED IN v3 ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────

    Problem with v2 (gold flame):
      The tall teardrop/flame shape was flagged as anatomically ambiguous — the
      narrow base broadening into a rounded body with a pointed tip reads as
      something other than a flame when the context (fire, heat) is not obvious.
      The shape needs to be completely unambiguous at a glance.

    What v3 does instead:
      A NESTED DIAMOND (gem) motif — three concentric rotated squares:

        1. Outer diamond  — bold gold outline, near-invisible warm fill.
           Fills most of the viewport. Commands the space.

        2. Middle diamond — thinner stroke in a slightly warmer/brighter gold.
           Sits inside the outer, creating a gem-cut depth illusion.
           The gap between outer and middle reads as a bevelled edge.

        3. Centre diamond — small solid filled diamond at the exact centre.
           Acts as the focal point / "stone" of the gem. Draws the eye inward.

    WHY a diamond and not another shape:
      • Pure geometry — cannot be misread as anything biological or symbolic
        beyond what it is: a gem / diamond / rotated square.
      • Completely distinct from all five rank badges:
          Observer   → eye / iris shape
          Initiate   → upward triangle
          Challenger → shield
          Conqueror  → crossbow
          Sovereign  → crown
        A diamond (rotated square) shares zero visual language with any of these.
      • "Diamond" thematically fits "Mission: Uncomfortable" — a diamond forms
        under pressure. The app is about applying pressure to yourself.
      • Static shape with no circular elements → cannot be confused with the
        circular glow rings used on the rank badges on DashboardScreen.

    WHY no animation baked into the drawable:
      All animation (entrance fade, scale, glow) is handled in WelcomeScreen.kt.
      The drawable is a pure static shape so it can be reused or restyled without
      touching the animation layer.

    ─── COLOURS USED ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

      #C8A84B  — ColorAccentGold  (outer diamond stroke, centre fill)
      #DCB65C  — ColorHotGold     (middle diamond stroke — slightly warmer/brighter)
      #1AC8A84B — 10% alpha gold fill on outer diamond (barely-there warmth, not
                  opaque enough to read as a filled shape — keeps it feeling open)

    ─── FILE LOCATION ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

      app/src/main/res/drawable/emblem_welcome.xml

-->

<vector xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android"
    android:width="100dp"
    android:height="100dp"
    android:viewportWidth="100"
    android:viewportHeight="100">

    <!--
        ── 1. OUTER DIAMOND ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
        The four corners sit 4dp from each edge of the viewport, so the shape
        fills almost the entire canvas. Bold 2.5dp stroke at ColorAccentGold.
        Fill is 10% alpha gold — just enough warmth to separate the inside from
        the background without making it look like a solid shape.
        strokeLineCap and strokeLineJoin set to "round" so the four points are
        very slightly softened — avoids the harsh mechanical look of sharp mitre
        joins while keeping the shape clearly angular.
    -->
    <path
        android:pathData="M 50,4 L 96,50 L 50,96 L 4,50 Z"
        android:fillColor="#1AC8A84B"
        android:strokeColor="#C8A84B"
        android:strokeWidth="2.5"
        android:strokeLineCap="round"
        android:strokeLineJoin="round"/>

    <!--
        ── 2. MIDDLE DIAMOND ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
        Corners at 20% inset from each edge (20,50 / 50,20 / 80,50 / 50,80).
        Thinner stroke (1.2dp) in ColorHotGold — slightly warmer and brighter
        than the outer. The warmer inner ring creates a bevelled-edge illusion:
        the space between outer and middle reads as a polished facet catching
        more light than the outer face.
        No fill — transparent interior so the centre diamond reads cleanly.
        Stroke alpha 0.75 so it is clearly visible but subordinate to the outer.
    -->
    <path
        android:pathData="M 50,20 L 80,50 L 50,80 L 20,50 Z"
        android:fillColor="#00000000"
        android:strokeColor="#DCB65C"
        android:strokeWidth="1.2"
        android:strokeLineCap="round"
        android:strokeLineJoin="round"
        android:strokeAlpha="0.75"/>

    <!--
        ── 3. CENTRE DIAMOND ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
        A small solid gold diamond at the exact geometric centre (50,50).
        Corner offsets of ±7 units give a diamond that is 14×14 units —
        large enough to be clearly visible at 150dp but small enough to read as
        a "stone" or focal point rather than another ring.
        Solid fill in ColorHotGold. No stroke needed — the filled shape is
        already crisp at this size.
        This is the eye magnet: the viewer's gaze travels inward from the outer
        diamond → middle ring → centre stone, mimicking the way a cut gem draws
        the eye to its table facet.
    -->
    <path
        android:pathData="M 50,43 L 57,50 L 50,57 L 43,50 Z"
        android:fillColor="#DCB65C"/>

</vector>
